Cymbopogon nardus var. mahapengiri

   [5126.jpg]
    Authority   (L.) Rendle
      Family    Liliopsida:Commelinidae:Cyperales:Gramineae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 5126

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A robust, stoloniferous grass with relatively broad
   leaves reaching a height of 0.5-1 m. USES An oil is extracted and used
   in perfumed products and synthetic menthol. The Java variety yields up
   to twice as much essential oil as the Ceylon type and the oil is of
   better quality. Java citronella oil contains 40-50% citronellal.
   GROWING PERIOD Perennial. The first cutting is usually taken 180-270
   days after planting, subsequent harvesting is done every 90-120 days
   and the crop last for 4-5 years, as yields steadily decline. COMMON
   NAMES Citronella grass, Nardus grass Java, Naid grass. FURTHER INF
   Scientific synonym: C. winterianus. Citronella grass can be grown from
   sea level to 1000 m in elevation. Average yields of essential oil is
   usually between 45-110 kg/ha. Mentioned as a useful agroforestry
   species.

   Sources
   SOURCES (C. nardus (L.) Rendle var. mahapengiri)
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 98 [USE]
   Duke J 1979 pp 94 [PH, RAIN, TEMP]
   Duke J 1975 pp 14 [PH, RAIN, TEMP]
   Purseglove J 1972 pp 140-141 [RAIN, LIG, TEXT, DRA]
   Skerman P 1990 pp 303-305 [RAIN, USE]

